ce (according to the Neoplatonic theory of the soul); (4) the real purpose and nature of the hymns 6-8 (uncorrectly considered “tout court” as christological), and the original structure of the eighth hymn (to be divided in two different poems). Moreover, the study of ancient and late antique metrical and musical theories reveals hitherto unexpected features about both production and performance of Synesius’ hymns.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Italian.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aHymns, GreekxCriticism, Textual. 4aEdition. 4aHymnen. 4aSpätantike. 4aSynesius. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aEdition.  aHymns.  aLate Antiquity.  aSynesius.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET ALTERTUM 2011z9783110261219oZDB-23-DGD0 cprintz978311027448640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311027973340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110279733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110279733/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2011  aZDB-23-DGGb2011  aZDB-23-GCNc2000d2014